30.article.11737}}\n*{{GroveOnline|title=Pachelbel, Johann|author= Nolte, Ewald V.|author2=Butt, John|access-date=6 April 2018|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.50932}}\n*{{citation|title=Hans Holbein and Miles Coverdale: A New Woodcut|first1=David|last1= Paisey|first2= Giulia|last2= Bartrum|\njournal=Print Quarterly|volume=26|issue=3|year=2009|pages=227\u2013253|jstor=43826083}}\n*{{citation|first=J.A.|last=Reincken|authorlink=Johann Adam Reincken|title=Complete Organ Works|isbn=978-3795797737|editor-last=Dirksen|editor-first=Pieter|publisher=[[Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel]]|chapter=Preface|year=2005|pages=7\u201310, 83}}\n*{{citation|first=J.A.|last=Reincken|authorlink=Johann Adam Reincken|title=Complete Organ Works|edition=2nd|ismn=9790001137416|editor-last=Beckmann|editor-first=Klaus|publisher=[[Schott Music]]|chapter=Preface, Critical commentary, Facsimiles|year=2008|pages=9\u201312, 58\u201361, 61\u201364}}\n*{{GroveOnline|title=Sch\u00fctz, Heinrich||author= Rifkin, Joshua|author2=Linfield, Eva|author3=McCulloch, Derek|author4=Baron, Stephen|access-date=12 March 2018|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.45997}}\n*{{citation|title=The Routledge Research Companion to Johann Sebastian Bach|editor-first=Robin A. |editor-last=Leaver|publisher=Taylor & Francis| year=2017|isbn=9781409417903|chapter=The Alt-Bachisches Archiv|first=Steven|last=Rose|page=213\u2013236}}\n*{{citation|first=Arnold|last= Schering|title=Johann Philipp Kirnberger als Herausgeber Bachscher Chor\u00e4le|journal= Bach-Jahrbuch|volume=15|year=1918|pages=141\u2013149}}\n*{{citation|title=J.S. Bach|series=Oxford composer companions|editor=Malcolm Boyd|editor2=John Butt|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=2003|edition=2nd|isbn=0198606206|chapter=Stylus Phantasticus|last=Schulenberg|first=David|page=[https://archive.org/details/jsbach0000unse/page/471 471]|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/jsbach0000unse/page/471}}\n*{{citation|last=Schulenberg|first= David|title=The keyboard music of J.S. Bach|edition=2nd|year=2006|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=0415974003}}\n*{{citation|first=Hans-Joachim|last=Schulze|journal=Bach-Jahrbuch|volume=69|year=1983|pages=81\u2013100|language=de|title=150 St\u00fcck von den Bachischen Erben}}\n*{{citation|title=J.S. Bach, the Breitkopfs, and Eighteenth-century Music Trade|series=Bach Perspectives|volume=2|editor=George B. Stauffer|publisher=[[University of Nebraska Press]]|year= 1996|isbn=0803210442|first=Hans-Joachim|last=Schulze|chapter=J.S. Bach's Vocal Works in the Breitkopf Nonthematic Catalogs of 1761 to 1836|pages=35\u201352}}\n*{{citation |last1=Sch\u00fctz |first1=Heinrich |author-link1=Heinrich Sch\u00fctz |date=1628 |chapter=Der CXXXVII. Psalm |chapter-url=http://daten.digitale-sammlungen.de/bsb00094385/image_572 |title=Psalmen Davids: Hiebevorn in Teutzsche Reimen gebracht durch D. Cornelium Beckern |language=de |location=Freiberg |publisher=Georg Hoffman |pages=560\u2013564 |postscript=. {{RISM|00000990058712}} |title-link=Psalmen Davids: Hiebevorn in Teutzsche Reimen gebracht durch D. Cornelium Beckern }}\n*{{citation|last1=Sch\u00fctz |first1=Heinrich |author-link1=Heinrich Sch\u00fctz |translator-last=Johnston |translator-first=Gregory S. |date=2013 |title=A Heinrich Sch\u00fctz Reader: Letters and Documents in Translation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F3VTON3VMDoC |location=United States |publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=F3VTON3VMDoC&pg=PA62 62] |isbn=978-0199812202}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Shannon |first1=John R. |date=2012 |title=The Evolution of Organ Music in the 17th Century: A Study of European Styles |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GB64QIHirTEC |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786488667 |ref=harv}}\n*{{GroveOnline|title=Schein, Johann Hermann||author= Snyder, Kerala Y.|author2=Johnson, Gregory S.|access-date=12 March 2018|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.24787}}\n*{{citation|last=Spagnoli|first=Gina|title=The Early Baroque Era: From the late 16th century to the 1660s|chapter=Dresden at the Time of Heinrich Sch\u00fctz|editor-last=Price|editor-first=Curtis|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]|year=1993|pages=164\u2013184}}\n*{{citation|url=https://archive.org/details/bachorgelbuchlei0000stin/page/2|title=Bach: The Orgelb\u00fcchlein|year=1999|first=Russell|last=Stinson|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780193862142|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bachorgelbuchlei0000stin/page/2 2\u20139]|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780193862142.001.0001}}\n*{{citation|title=J.S. Bach's Great Eighteen Organ Chorales|first=Russell|last= Stinson|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year= 2001|isbn=0-19-516556-X|url=http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195116663.001.0001/acprof-9780195116663-chapter-4|pages=78\u201380|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195116663.001.0001}}\n*{{citation|title=J. S. Bach at His Royal Instrument: Essays on His Organ Works|first=Russel|last=Stinson|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year= 2012|page=16|isbn=978-0199917235}}\n*{{citation|first=Charles Sanford|last=Terry|authorlink=Charles Sanford Terry (historian)|title= Bach's Chorals, vol. III|year=1921| url=https://archive.org/stream/bachschorals03terr#page/100/mode/2up|pages=101\u2013104|publisher=Cambridge, The University Press}}\n*{{citation|title=The Routledge Research Companion to Johann Sebastian Bach|editor-first=Robin A. |editor-last=Leaver|publisher=Taylor & Francis| year=2017|isbn=9781409417903|chapter=Manuscripts|first=Yo|last=Tomita|pages=47\u201388}}\n*{{citation|title=The Singing of the Strasbourg Protestants, 1523-1541|series=St Andrews Studies in Reformation History|first=Daniel|last= Trocm\u00e9-Latter|publisher=Ashgate|year= 2015|isbn=9781472432063}}\n*{{citation|title=Histories of Heinrich Sch\u00fctz|first=Bettina|last= Varwig|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year= 2011|isbn=978-1139502016}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wachowski |first1=Gerd |author-link1=:de:Gerd Wachowski |date=1983 |chapter=Die vierstimmigen Chor\u00e4le Johann Sebastian Bachs: Untersuchungen zu den Druckausgaben von 1765 bis 1932 und zur Frage der Authentizit\u00e4t |trans-chapter=The four-part chorales of Johann Sebastian Bach: research into the printed editions from 1765 to 1732 and regarding the question of authenticity |chapter-url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/article/view/2434 |editor1-last=Schulze |editor1-first=Hans-Joachim |editor1-link=Hans-Joachim Schulze |editor2-last=Wolff |editor2-first=Christoph |editor2-link=Christoph Wolff |title=Bach-Jahrbuch 1983 |trans-title=Bach Yearbook 1983 |url=https://journals.qucosa.de/ejournals/bjb/issue/view/145 |series=[[Bach-Jahrbuch]] |language=de |volume=69 |others=[[Neue Bachgesellschaft]] |location=Berlin |publisher={{ill|Evangelische Verlagsanstalt|de}} |pages=51\u201379 |doi=10.13141/bjb.v1983 |isbn= |issn=0084-7682 |ref=harv }}\n*{{citation|title=Wer ist wer im Gesangbuch?|language=de|series=Handbuch Zum Evangelischen Gesangbuch|volume=2|editor-first=Wolfgang|editor-last=Herbst|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|year= 2001|isbn=3525503237|chapter=Wolfgang Dachstein|first=\u00c9dith|last=Weber|pages=70\u201371}}\n*{{citation |last1=Werner |first1=Wilfried |date=2016 |chapter='Nicht mitzuhassen, mitzulieben bin ich da!' Exegese und Predigt zu Psalm 137|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=adxtDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA197 |editor1-last=Hartlapp |editor1-first=Johannes |editor2-last=Cramer |editor2-first=Andrea |title=\"Und was ich noch sagen wollte ...\": Festschrift f\u00fcr Wolfgang Kabus zum 80. Geburtstag |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=adxtDQAAQBAJ |language=de |publisher=Frank & Timme |pages=193\u2013216 |isbn=978-3732903139}}\n*{{citation|first=Peter|last=Williams|title=The Organ Music of J.S. Bach, Volume II: BWV 599\u2013771, etc.| series=Cambridge Studies in Music|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1980|isbn=0-521-31700-2}}\n*{{citation|first=Peter|last=Williams|title=The Organ Music of J. S. Bach|edition=2nd|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=2003|isbn=0-521-89115-9}}\n*{{citation|title=Bach: A Musical Biography|first=Peter|last= Williams|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year= 2016|isbn=978-1107139251}}\n*{{citation|title=J.S. Bach as Organist|year=1986|publisher=[[Indiana University Press]]|editor=George Stauffer|editor2=Ernest May|chapter=Johann Adam Reinken and Johann Sebastian Bach: On the Context of Bach's Early Works| first=Christoph|last=Wolff|pages=57\u201380|isbn= 0713452625}}\n*{{citation|last=Yearsley|first=David|title=Bach Discoveries|year=2009|journal=[[Early Music]]|pages=489\u2013492|volume=37|issue=3|doi=10.1093/em/cap055}}\n*{{citation|title=Bach's Feet: The Organ Pedals in European Culture|first=David |last=Yearsley|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year= 2012|isbn=978-1139500111|pages=94\u201397}}\n* {{citation |last1=Zahn |first1=Johannes |author-link1=Johannes Zahn |date=1891 |chapter=7663 |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/1508286757bsb11304502#page/n513/mode/2up |title=Die Melodien der deutschen evangelischen Kirchenlieder |volume=[https://archive.org/details/1508286757bsb11304502 IV] |location=G\u00fctersloh |publisher=[[Bertelsmann]] |language=de |pages=508\u2013509 |title-link=scores:Die Melodien der deutschen evangelischen Kirchenlieder (Zahn, Johannes) }}\n* {{citation |last1=Zahn |first1=Johannes |author-link1=Johannes Zahn |date=1893|title=Die Melodien der deutschen evangelischen Kirchenlieder |volume=[https://archive.org/details/1508288358bsb11304504 VI] |location=G\u00fctersloh |publisher=[[Bertelsmann]] |language=de |title-link=scores:Die Melodien der deutschen evangelischen Kirchenlieder (Zahn, Johannes) }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{IMSLP|work=An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon (Schein, Johann Hermann)|cname =An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, Opella nova (Geistliche Konzerte, Leipzig, 1618) by Johann Hermann Schein}}\n* {{IMSLP|work= Becker Psalter, Op.5 (Sch\u00fctz, Heinrich)|cname =An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, Becker Psalter, Op.5 (Psalmen Davids, Freiberg, 1628) by\nHeinrich Sch\u00fctz}}\n* {{IMSLP|work=An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, P.17 (Pachelbel, Johann)|cname =An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, P.17 |work2=An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, P.18 (Pachelbel, Johann)|cname2=An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, P.18|work3=An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, P.20 (Pachelbel, Johann)|cname3=An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, P.20 by Johann Pachelbel}}\n* {{IMSLP|work=Complete Organ Works (Reincken, Johann Adam)|cname=An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon (Complete Organ Works, ed. Klaus Beckmann, Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel, 1974) by Johann Adam Reincken}}\n* {{IMSLP|work=An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, BWV 267 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname =An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, BWV 267|work2=An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon, BWV 653 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname2=BWV 653, by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n* [http://colmarisches.free.fr/Choralmelodien/Chorals/AnWasserflussen.html Zu Fassungen der Melodie in Els\u00e4ssischen Gesangb\u00fcchern] colmarisches.free.fr\n* [https://www.dzb.de/index.php?site_id=2.1.3.3&id=3280&show=titles Glebe, Karl ; Heinermann, Otto: / Vorspiele zum deutsch-evangelischen Gesangbuch f\u00fcr Orgel] dzb.de\n* G. W. Fink: [https://books.google.de/books?id=wuMqAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA38 No. 24] Allgemeine musikalische Zeitung, Volume 38, 1836\n* {{cite web| url = http://www.thescrollensemble.com/en/programme-notes-an-wasserflussen-babylon/| title = An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylons|publisher = The Scroll Ensemble| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}\n*{{cite web| url= http://www.bach-chorales.com/ |title= The Four-Part Chorales of J.S. Bach|access-date=9 April 2018|first=Luke|last=Dahn}}\n\n{{Hymns and songs based on Psalms}}\n{{German Lutheran hymns}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:An Wasserflussen Babylon}}\n[[Category:Psalm settings]]\n[[Category:Lutheran hymns based on Psalms]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = \"{{Lang|de|An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon|italic=no}}\"\n| type                = [[Lutheran hymn]]\n| image               = File:Super-Flumina-Babylonis-Stra\u00dfburger-Gesangbuch-1541.jpg\n| image_upright       = 1.2\n| caption             = ''Super Flumina Babylonis'', \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon,\" from the 1541 ''Stra\u00dfburger Gesangbuch''\n| Title_English       = By the rivers of Babylon\n| text                = [[Wolfgang Dachstein]]\n| based_on            = [[Psalm 137]]\n| language            = German\n| published           = {{Start date|1525}}\n| misc                = <!--{{Audio|Gelobet seist du, Jesu Christ.mid|Tune}} -->\n}}\n\n\"'''An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon'''\" (By the rivers of [[Babylon]]) is a [[Lutheran hymn]] by [[Wolfgang Dachstein]], which was first published in [[Strasbourg]] in 1525. The text of the hymn is a paraphrase of [[Psalm 137]]. Its singing tune, which is the best known part of the hymn and Dachstein's best known melody, was popularised as [[chorale]] tune of [[Paul Gerhardt]]'s 17th-century [[Passion of Jesus|Passion]] hymn \"[[Ein L\u00e4mmlein geht und tr\u00e4gt die Schuld]]\". With this hymn text, Dachstein's tune is included in the Protestant hymnal ''[[Evangelisches Gesangbuch]]''.\n\nSeveral vocal and [[pipe organ|organ]] settings of the hymn \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" have been composed in the 17th and 18th century, including 4-part harmonisations by [[Johann Hermann Schein]], [[Heinrich Sch\u00fctz]] and [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. In the second half of the 17th century, [[Johann Pachelbel]], [[Johann Adam Reincken]] and Bach's [[First Cousin Once Removed|cousin]], [[Johann Christoph Bach|Johann Christoph]], arranged settings for [[chorale prelude]]s.\n\nThe arrangements of \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" by Reincken and Pachelbel form the earliest extant transcriptions of Bach, copied on a 1700 [[organ tablature]] in [[L\u00fcneburg]] when he was still a youth; remarkably, they were only unearthed in [[Weimar]] in 2005.\n\nIn 1720, in a celebrated organ concert at [[St. Catherine's Church, Hamburg|Hamburg]], Bach extemporised a chorale setting of \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" in the presence of Reincken, two years before his death. Bach also composed three versions of the chorale prelude \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" as part of the ''[[Great Eighteen Chorale Preludes]]'', the last dating from 1740\u20131750 in [[Leipzig]], possibly as a tribute to Reincken's well-known chorale fantasia.\n\n== History and context ==\n[[File:Nuremberg-Chronicles-1493-Strasburg-Argentina.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Woodcut of [[Strasbourg]] from ''[[Nuremberg Chronicle]]'', [[Hartmann Schedel]], 1493: [[Strasbourg Cathedral|Cathedral]]&nbsp;(r) and [[St Thomas' Church, Strasbourg|St Thomas]]&nbsp;(l)]]\n\n[[File:Stra\u00dfburger-Gesangbuch-1541.jpeg|thumb|upright=1.1|Title page of the 1541 ''Stra\u00dfburger Gesangbuch'']]\n[[File:Martin Bucer by Boissard.png|thumb|Martin Bucer, \"Icones quinquaginta vivorum\": engraving by [[Jean-Jacques Boissard]]]]\n\n\"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" is a Lutheran hymn written in 1525 and attributed to [[Wolfgang Dachstein]], organist at [[St Thomas' Church, Strasbourg]].<ref name=\"Leahy\">{{harvnb|Leahy|2011|pages=37\u201338, 53}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Terry|1921|pages=101\u2013103}}</ref><ref name=\"Julian 1907\">{{harvnb|Julian|1907}}</ref> The hymn is a closely paraphrased versification of [[Psalm 137]], \"By the rivers of Babylon\", a lamentation for Jerusalem, exiled in Babylon.<ref name=\"Leahy\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Stinson|2001|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1uCUsdmP7Z4C&pg=PA78 78]}}</ref> Its text and melody, [[Zahn number]] 7663, first appeared in [[Strasbourg]] in 1525 in [[Wolf K\u00f6pphel]]'s ''Das dritt theil Stra\u00dfburger kirchenampt''.<ref name=\"Leahy\"/><ref name=\"Zahn1891\">{{harvnb|Zahn|1891}}</ref> This Strasbourg tract, which comprised the third part of the Lutheran service, is now lost.<ref name=\"Zahn1891\" /> Despite the lost tract from 1525, the Strasbourg hymn appeared in print in 1526 in ''Psalmen, Gebett und Kirchenordnung wie sie zu Stra\u00dfburg gehalten werden'' and later.<ref name=\"Zahn1891\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Zahn|1893|page=[https://archive.org/stream/1508288358bsb11304504#page/n15/mode/2up 7]}}</ref><ref name=\"Trocm\u00e9-Latter2015pp255-265\">{{harvnb|Trocm\u00e9-Latter|2015|pages=255\u2013265}}</ref>\n\nWolfgang Egeloph Dachstein was born in 1487 in [[Offenburg]] in the [[Black Forest]]. In 1503 he became a fellow student with [[Martin Luther]] at the [[University of Erfurt]]. He entered the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] monastic order in around 1520 in Strasbourg, where he started a collaboration with [[Matthias Greitter|Matthias Greiter]], a friend and contemporary. Greiter was born in 1495 in [[Aichach]], near [[Augsburg]] in [[Bavaria]], where he attended a Latin school, before enrolling in [[theology]] at the [[University of Freiburg]] in 1510 and becoming a monk in Strasbourg in 1520.<ref>{{harvnb|Weber|2001|pages=70\u201371}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Brusniak|2001|pages=121\u2013122}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Forna\u00e7on, Siegfried|1957|page=465}}</ref><ref> {{harvnb|M\u00fcller, Hans-Christian|1966|pages=41\u201342}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Trocm\u00e9-Latter|2015|pages=28\u201332, 90\u201396, 201}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Reformation]], Protestantism was adopted in Strasbourg in 1524. The reforms involved the introduction of the German vernacular, the use of [[Agenda (liturgy)|Lutheran liturgy]] (\"Gottesdienstordnung\") and congregational singing. Both Greiter and Dachstein renounced their monastic vows and married in Alsace. Their association continued, with Greiter becoming a cantor in the Cathedral and Dachstein an organist at St Thomas. Both played an important role in the musical life of Strasbourg, with many contributions to Lutheran hymns and psalms. [[Daniel Specklin]], a 16th-century architect from [[Alsace]], where the region [[Dachstein, Bas-Rhin|Dachstein]] takes its name, described in detail how the pair engaged in \"das evangelium\" and \"vil gute psalmen\". A costly edition of the ''Stra\u00dfburger Gesangbuch'' was published by K\u00f6pphel in 1541, with a preface by the Lutheran reformer [[Martin Bucer]]: the title, text and psalm were printed in characteristic red and black with woodcuts by [[Hans Baldung]]. During the [[Counter-Reformation]], however, the [[Augsburg Interim]] resulted in Strasbourg reinstating Catholicism in October 1549: both Dachstein and Greiter renounced Protestantism and Bucer was sent into exile in [[England]], where under [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]] he became [[Regius Professor of Divinity#Professors at Cambridge|Regius Professor of Divinity]].<ref name=\"DachGreit-FlB\"> See:\n*{{harvnb|Weber|2001|pages=70\u201371}}\n*{{harvnb|Brusniak|2001|pages=121\u2013122}}\n*{{harvnb|Forna\u00e7on, Siegfried|1957|page=465}}\n*{{harvnb|M\u00fcller, Hans-Christian|1966|pages=41\u201342}}\n*{{harvnb|Trocm\u00e9-Latter|2015|pages=28\u201332, 90\u201396, 201}}</ref><!--<ref name=\"Grove-FlB\"> See also:\n*{{harvnb|M\u00fcller|Migliorini|2001}}\n*{{harvnb|M\u00fcller|Davies|2001}}</ref> --><ref>{{harvnb|Trocm\u00e9-Latter|2015|pages=233\u2013234}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Hopf|1946|pages=1\u201316}}</ref>\n\nDachstein's hymn \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" was rapidly distributed\u2014it was printed in Luther's 1545 ''Babstsches Gesangbuch''<ref>{{harvnb|Krummacher|2001|pages=194\u2013195}}</ref>\u2014and spread to most Lutheran hymnbooks by central Germany.<ref name=\"Leahy\"/> After the [[Sack of Magdeburg]] in 1631, during the [[Thirty Years' War]], it was decreed that Dachstein's 137th Psalm would be sung every year as part of the ceremonies to commemorate the destruction of [[Magdeburg]].<ref name=\"Werner2016p205\">{{harvnb|Werner|2016|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=adxtDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA205 205]}}</ref>\n\nThe melody of the hymn became better known than its text, through the association of that melody with [[Paul Gerhardt]]'s 17th-century [[Passion of Jesus|Passion]] hymn \"[[Ein L\u00e4mmlein geht und tr\u00e4gt die Schuld]]\".<ref name=\"Zahn1891\" /><ref name=\"Werner2016p205\" /> With that hymn text, the hymn tune of \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" is adopted as EG&nbsp;83 in the Protestant hymnal ''[[Evangelisches Gesangbuch]]''.<ref name=\"Axmacher\" /><ref name=\"W\u00fcrttemberg\" /> The hymn tune is Dachstein's best known composition.<ref name=\"Julian 1907\" />\n\n[[Miles Coverdale]] provided an early English translation in the Tudor Protestant Hymnal ''\"Ghostly Psalms and Spiritual Songs,\"'' 1539.  These Lutheran versifications were written in continental [[Europe]] while Coverdale was in exile from England.<ref> {{harvnb|Coverdale|1846|pages=571\u2013572}}</ref><ref name=\"Terry\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Trocm\u00e9-Latter|2015|pages=237\u2013239}}</ref>\n\n== Text ==\nThe Lutheran text of Dachstein first appeared in 1525.<ref name=\"Leahy\">{{harvnb|Leahy|2011|pages=37\u201338, 53}}</ref> The English translation by Miles Coverdale dates from 1539.<ref name=\"Terry\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Coverdale|1846|pages=571\u2013572}}</ref>\n{|\n|\n'''German text'''\n|\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''English translation'''\n|-\n|\n<poem>\n1. An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon,\n   Da sa\u00dfen wir mit Schmerzen;\n   Als wir gedachten an Sion,\n   Da weinten wir von Herzen;\n   Wir hingen auf mit schwerem Mut\n   Die Orgeln und die Harfen gut\n   An ihre B\u00e4um der Weiden,\n   Die drinnen sind in ihrem Land,\n   Da mussten wir viel Schmach und Schand\n   T\u00e4glich von ihnen leiden.\n</poem>\n|\n<poem>\n     At the ryvers of Babilon,\n     There sat we downe ryght hevely;\n     Even whan we thought upon Sion,\n     We wepte together sorofully.\n     For we were in soch hevynes,\n     That we forgat al our merynes,\n     And lefte of all oure sporte and playe:\n     On the willye trees that were thereby\n     We hanged up oure harpes truly,\n     And morned sore both nyght and daye.\n</poem>\n|-\n|\n<poem>\n2. Die uns gefangen hielten lang\n   So hart an selben Orten\n   Begehrten von uns ein Gesang\n   Mit gar sp\u00f6ttlichen Worten\n   Und suchten in der Traurigkeit\n   Ein fr\u00f6hlichn Gsang in unserm Leid\n   Ach lieber tut uns singen\n   Ein Lobgesang, ein Liedlein schon\n   Von den Gedichten aus Zion,\n   Das fr\u00f6hlich tut erklingen.\n</poem>\n|\n<poem>\n    They that toke us so cruelly,\n    And led us bounde into pryson,\n    Requyred of us some melody.\n    With wordes full of derision.\n    When we had hanged oure harpes alwaye,\n    This cruell folke to us coulde saye:\n    Now let us heare some mery songe,\n    Synge us a songe of some swete toyne,\n    As ye were wont to synge at Sion,\n    Where ye have lerned to synge so longe.\n</poem>\n|-\n|\n<poem>\n3. Wie sollen wir in solchem Zwang\n   Und Elend, jetzt vorhanden,\n   Dem Herren singen ein Gesang\n   Sogar in fremden Landen?\n   Jerusalem, vergiss ich dein,\n   So wolle Gott, der G'rechte, mein\n   Vergessen in meim Leben,\n   Wenn ich nicht dein bleib eingedenk\n   Mein Zunge sich oben ane h\u00e4ng\n   Und bleib am Rachen kleben.\n</poem>\n|\n<poem>\n    To whome we answered soberly:\n    Beholde now are we in youre honde:\n    How shulde we under captivite\n    Synge to the Lorde in a straunge londe?\n    Hierusalem, I say to the,\n    Yf I remember the not truly,\n    My honde playe on the harpe no more:\n    Yf I thynke not on the alwaye,\n    Let my tonge cleve to my mouth for aye,\n    And let me loose my speache therfore.\n</poem>\n|-\n|\n<poem>\n4. Ja, wenn ich nicht mit ganzem Fleiss,\n   Jerusalem, dich ehre,\n   Im Anfang meiner Freude Preis\n   Von jetzt und immermehre,\n   Gedenk der Kinder Edom sehr,\n   Am Tag Jerusalem, o Herr,\n   Die in der Bosheit sprechen:\n   Reiss ab, reiss ab zu aller Stund,\n   Vertilg sie gar bis auf den Grund,\n   Den Boden wolln wir brechen!\n</poem>\n|\n<poem>\n     Yee, above all myrth and pastaunce,\n     Hierusalem, I preferre the.\n     Lorde, call to thy remembraunce\n     The sonnes of Edom ryght strately,\n     In the daye of the destruction,\n     Which at Hierusalem was done;\n     For they sayd in theyr cruelnes,\n     Downe with it, downe with it, destroye it all;\n     Downe with it soone, that it may fall,\n     Laye it to the grounde all that there is.\n</poem>\n|-\n|\n<poem>\n5. Die schn\u00f6de Tochter Babylon,\n   Zerbrochen und zerst\u00f6ret,\n   Wohl dem, der wird dir gebn den Lohn\n   Und dir, das wiederkehret,\n   Dein \u00dcbermut und Schalkheit gross,\n   Und misst dir auch mit solchem Mass,\n   Wie du uns hast gemessen;\n   Wohl dem, der deine Kinder klein\n   Erfasst und schl\u00e4gt sie an ein Stein,\n   Damit dein wird vergessen!<ref>Modernised orthography, while the original wording is found in [[Philipp Wackernagel]]: ''Das deutsche Kirchenlied von der \u00e4ltesten Zeit bis zu Anfang des 17. Jahrhunderts''. [https://books.google.com/books?id=9dZDAQAAMAAJ Vol. III.] Teubner, 1870, [https://books.google.com/books?id=9dZDAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA98 No.&nbsp;135 (p.&nbsp;98)]</ref>\n</poem>\n|\n<poem>\n     O thou cite of Babilon,\n     Thou thy selfe shalt be destroyed.\n     Truly blessed shall be that man\n     Which, even as thou hast deserved,\n     Shall rewarde the with soch kyndnesse\n     As thou hast shewed to us gyltlesse,\n     Which never had offended the.\n     Blessed shall he be that for the nones\n     Shall throwe thy chyldren agaynst the stones,\n     To brynge the out of memorie.\n</poem>\n|}\n\n== Hymn tune ==\nBelow is the 1525 hymn tune by Wolfgang Dachstein.\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\">\n{ \\key f \\major\n\n\\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n\\tempo 2=72\n\\set Staff.midiInstrument = \"english horn\"\n\\override Score.TimeSignature #'transparent = ##t\n\\override Score.BarNumber  #'transparent = ##t\n\\time 6/2\nc''2 d''4 c'' a'2 c'' bes'4 bes' a'2\ng'2 a'4 bes' c''2 bes'4 a' g'2 f'\n\nc''2 d''4 c'' a'2 c'' bes'4 bes' a'2\ng'2 a'4 bes' c''2 bes'4 a' g'2 f'\n\nf'2 g'4 a' bes'2 g' a'4 g' f'2\nf'2 a'4 bes' c''2 d'' a'4 bes' c''2\n\\time 5/2\na'2 c''4 d'' c'' a' bes'2 a'\n\\time 7/2\nd''2 d''4 d'' g'2 c'' bes'4( g') a'2 g'\nbes'2 a'4 g' f'2 g' e'4 (f') d'2 c'\n\\time 8/2\nc'2 f'4 g' a' bes' c''2(a'4 bes' g'2) f'1\n\\bar \"|.\"}\n</score>\n\n== Musical settings ==\n=== Vocal settings ===\n[[File:Georg Rhau.jpg|thumb|upright|Georg Rhau, the [[Thomaskantor]]: woodcut by  [[Lucas Cranach the Elder]] {{circa|1542}}]]\n\n[[File:Johann Hermann Schein 1620.jpg|thumb|upright|Johann Hermann Schein, 1620, Leipzig]]\nThere are several vocal works based on the hymn \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\". In 1544 [[Georg Rhau]] composed two settings for several parts for his collection ''Neue Deutsche Geistliche Ges\u00e4nge f\u00fcr die gemeinen Schulen''.<ref>{{GroveOnline|title=Rhau, Georg|author= Mattfield, Victor H.|access-date=8 April 2018|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.23314}}</ref> [[Lupus Hellinck]] also set a 4-part setting in 1544, as part of his ''Newe deudsche geistliche Gesenge''.<ref>{{GroveOnline|title=Hellinck, Lupus|author= Blackburn, Bonnie J..|access-date=10 April 2018|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.12738}}</ref>\nBenedictus Ducis wrote several settings in 3 and 4 parts of the hymn between 1541\u20131544.<ref>{{GroveOnline|title=Ducis, Benedictus|author= Thomayer, Klaus|access-date=10 April 2018|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.08254}}</ref>\n[[Sigmund Hemmel]] used the text in the 1550s in his four-part setting, with the cantus firmus in the tenor: ''Der gantz Psalter Davids, wie derselbig in teutsche Gesang verfasse'' was printed in 1569.<ref>{{GroveOnline|title=Hemmel, Sigmund|author= Brennecke, Wilfried|access-date=10 April 2018|url= https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.12770}}</ref>\n\nA native of [[Nuremberg]], [[Hans Leo Hassler]] was taught by [[Andrea Gabrieli]] in [[Venice]], where he excelled as a keyboard player and consorted with his younger uncle, [[Giovanni Gabrieli]]. Hassler's 4-part setting of \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" was composed in 1608.<ref>{{GroveOnline|title=Hassler, Hans Leos|author= Blankenberg, Walter|author2=Panetta, Vincent J.|access-date=10 April 2018|url= https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.12525}}</ref>\n\n[[Johann Hermann Schein]] composed a setting of \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" for two sopranos and instrumental accompaniment, which he published in 1617.<ref name=\"Schein\">{{GroveOnline|title=Schein, Johann Hermann|author= Snyder, Kerala J.|author2=Johnston, Gregory J.|access-date=10 April 2018|url=  https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.24787}}</ref> His 1627 ''Cantional'' contained a four-part setting of the hymn, a setting which was republished by [[Neu Leipziger Gesangbuch|Vopelius's ''Neu Leipziger Gesangbuch'']] (1682).<ref name=\"Schein\"/><ref>{{GroveOnline|title=Vopelius, Gottfried|author= Young, Percy M.|access-date=10 April 2018|url= https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.29682}}</ref><ref>[[Johann Hermann Schein]] (1627). [http://resolver.sub.uni-goettingen.de/purl?PPN778587517%7CLOG_0001 ''Cantional, Oder Gesangbuch Augspurgischer Confession''.] Leipzig: Schein, [https://gdz.sub.uni-goettingen.de/id/PPN778587517?tify=&#123;%22pages%22:&#91;674&#93;,%22view%22:%22info%22&#125; pp.&nbsp;325\u2013327]</ref><ref>[[Gottfried Vopelius]] (1682). ''[[Neu Leipziger Gesangbuch]]''. Leipzig: Christoph Klinger, [https://books.google.com/books?id=UmVkAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA706 pp.706\u2013709]</ref> In 1628 [[Heinrich Sch\u00fctz]] published a four-part harmonisation of ''\"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\"'', [[Sch\u00fctz-Werke-Verzeichnis|SWV]]&nbsp;242, in the ''Psalmen Davids, hiebevorn in teutzsche Reimen gebracht, durch D. Cornelium Beckern, und an jetzo mit ein hundert und drey eigenen Melodeyen \u2026 gestellet'', the ''[[Becker Psalter]]'', Op.&nbsp;5.<ref>{{GroveOnline|title=Sch\u00fctz, Heinrich||author= Rifkin, Joshua|author2=Linfield, Eva|author3=McCulloch, Derek|author4=Baron, Stephen|access-date=12 March 2018|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.45997}} </ref><ref>{{harvnb|Sch\u00fctz|2013}}</ref>\n[[Samuel Scheidt]], composed two settings of the hymn, SSWV 505 and 570, for soprano and organ in the ''Tabulatur-Buch hundert geistlicher Lieder und Psalmen'' of 1650.<ref>{{GroveOnline|title=Ducis, Benedictus|author= Snyder, Kerala J.|author2=Bush, Douglas|access-date=10 April 2018|url= https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.24785}}</ref>\n\n[[Franz Tunder]] composed a setting of the hymn for soprano, strings and continuo. Organist at the Marienkirche in L\u00fcbeck from 1646\u20131668, Tunder initiated his ''Abendmusik'' there. [[Dieterich Buxtehude|Buxtehude]] later married Tunder's daughter and succeeded him as organist at L\u00fcbeck.<ref> {{GroveOnline|title=Tunder, Franz|author= Snyder, Kerala J.|access-date=10 April 2018|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.28576 }}</ref>\n[[File:An-Wasserfl\u00fcssen-Babylon-Birnstiel-CPE-Bach-Cortot-Berlin-1765.jpg|thumb|upright|4-part chorale of \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" by J.S. Bach, edition of C.P.E. Bach & F.W. Birnstiel, 1765]]\nBach also composed a chorale harmonisation, [[BWV&nbsp;267]], which appeared around 1735 in the [[Dietel manuscript]].<ref>{{BDh|3441|0|2019-03-06|Source|{{nowrap|D-LEb Peters Ms. R 18}} (chorale collection Dietel)}}</ref><ref name=\"DahnBWV267\">Luke Dahn. [http://www.bach-chorales.com/BWV0267.htm BWV&nbsp;267] at {{url|www.bach-chorales.com}}. 2017.</ref><ref>{{IMSLP|work=149 Chorales, D-LEb Peters Ms. R 18 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname=149 Chorales, D-LEb Peters Ms. R 18 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)}}</ref> That harmonisation is found as well in [[G&nbsp;major]] and in [[A-flat major]] in 18th-century chorale collections, both as \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" and as \"Ein L\u00e4mmlein geht und tr\u00e4gt die Schuld\".<ref name=\"DahnBWV267\" /> For instance, its publication in the [[Johann Gottlob Immanuel Breitkopf|Breitkopf]] edition of the 1780s has it as No.&nbsp;5 in G&nbsp;major under the former title and as No.&nbsp;308 in A-flat major under the latter title.<ref name=\"DahnBWV267\" /><ref>{{IMSLP|work=371 Vierstimmige Choralges\u00e4nge (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname=371 Vierstimmige Choralges\u00e4nge (Bach, Johann Sebastian)}}</ref>{{sfn|Wachowski|1983|pp=68\u201369}} In [[Schemellis Gesangbuch|Schemelli's 1736 hymnal]], to which Bach collaborated, the [[key (music)|key]] of the \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" hymn, No.&nbsp;587, is given as \"D\", and that of seven other hymns sung to the same melody, including \"Ein L\u00e4mmlein geht und tr\u00e4gt die Schuld\", No.&nbsp;259, as \"G\".{{sfn|Leaver|2017|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=SCklDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA371 371]}}{{sfn|Schemelli|1736|pages=[http://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb10592514_00433.html 401] (No.&nbsp;587), [http://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb10592514_00203.html 171] (No.&nbsp;259)}}<ref>{{harvnb|Leaver|2014|pages=15\u201333}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Leaver|2017|page=371}}</ref>\n\nThe German composer of opera\u2014 ''[[Die lustigen Weiber von Windsor]]''\u2014and lieder, [[Otto Nicolai]] composed a 4-part setting of \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" in around 1832 as one of four songs in his op.17.<ref>{{GroveOnline|title=Nicolai, Otto|author= Konrad, Ulrich|access-date=10 April 2018|url= https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.19885}}</ref>\n\n=== Organ settings ===\n[[File:Eisenach-1647-Merian.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.0|Eisenach (1647), where Johann Christoph Bach became organist in 1665 and Johann Sebastian Bach was born in 1685]]\n[[File:Eisenacher Gesangbuch Tugendlieder.jpg|thumb|upright|Engraving of \"Eisenacher Gesangbuch\", 1673]]\n[[File:Musical Company by Johannes Voorhout (1674).jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|Musical Company, [[Johannes Voorhout]], 1674: Reincken at the harpsichord with Buxtehude at the viol]]\n[[File:Predigerkloster Erfurt.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|The Predigerkirche in Erfurt]]\nThe hymn also inspired seventeenth and early eighteenth century organ compositions in Northern Germany. Organ [[chorale prelude]]s and free works by [[Johann Christoph Bach]]<ref>{{harvnb|Rose|2017|pages=228\u2013229}}</ref> (Johann Sebastian's [[first cousin once removed]]), [[Johann Adam Reincken]]<ref>{{harvnb|Bei\u00dfwenger|2017|pages=243\u2013244}}</ref>, [[Johann Pachelbel]]<ref>{{harvnb|Bei\u00dfwenger|2017|page=242}}</ref> and [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]<ref>{{harvnb|Williams|2003|pages=347\u2013351}}</ref> have been based on \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\".\n\nThe 17th-century musical style of the ''[[stylus phantasticus]]'' covers the freely composed organ and harpsichord/clavichord works, including dance suites. They lie within two traditions: those from northern Germany, primarily for organ using the whole range of manual and pedal techniques, with passages of virtuoso exuberance; and those from central Germany, primarily for string keyboards, which have a more subdued style. [[Dietrich Buxtehude|Buxtehude]] and Reincken are important exponents of the northern school and Pachelbel those from the centre.<ref>{{harvnb|Schulenberg|2003|page=2003}}</ref><ref> {{harvnb|Schulenberg|2006|pages=34\u201336}}</ref><ref name=\"Collins\"> {{harvnb|Collins|2005|page=119}}</ref><ref> {{harvnb|Krummacher|1986|pages=157\u2013171}}</ref>\n\nJohann Christoph Bach was born in [[Arnstadt]] in 1642 and was appointed organist at St George's, the principal church of [[Eisenach]], from 1665. The 4-part chorale prelude \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" has the same kind of expressive [[dissonance (music)|dissonances]], with [[suspension (music)|suspensions]], as his ''Lamento'' \"Ach, da\u00df ich Wassers gnug h\u00e4tte\" for voice and strings.<ref> {{harvnb|Rose|2017|pages=203, 224\u2013226}}</ref>\n\nBorn probably in 1643, Reincken was the natural successor to Scheidemann as organist at the [[St. Catherine's Church, Hamburg]], with his musical interests extending beyond the church to the [[Hamburg Opera]] and the [[collegium musicum]]: as remarked by the 18th-century musician [[Johann Gottfried Walther]], his famous, dazzling and audacious chorale fantasia \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" probably marked that succession; its vast dimension of 327 bars and 10 chorale lines, some broken into two, encompass a wide range of techniques, such as its \"motet-like development, figuration of the chorale in the soprano, fore-imitation in diminished note values, introduction of counter-motifs, virtuoso passage work, double pedals, fragmentation, and echo effects.\"<ref> {{harvnb|Apel|1972|pages=605\u2013606}}</ref><ref name=\"Collins\"/><ref>*{{GroveOnline|title=Reincken, Johann Adam|author= Grapenthin, Ulf|access-date=2 April 2018|url=https://doi.org/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.23126}}</ref><ref> See also:\n*{{harvnb|Reincken|2005}}\n*{{harvnb|Reincken|2008}}</ref>\n\nPachelbel was born in [[Nuremberg]] in [[Bavaria]] and spent some of his early years as a musician in [[Vienna]] before being appointed as organist in the [[Predigerkirche (Erfurt)|Predigerkirche]], [[Erfurt]] in 1679\u20131690: part of his duties involved an annual concert in June lasting half an hour. Pachelbel's repertoire contained eight different types of chorale preludes, the last of which formed a \"hybrid combination-form\", one which he particularly favoured. The chorales on \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" were all of that type: a concise four-part fugue followed by a 3-part setting accompanying a slow cantus firmus in the soprano or bass; or a 4-part setting with the soprano in the cantus firmus.<!-- <ref>{{harvnb|Nulte|Butt|2001}}</ref>--><ref>{{harvnb|Butt|2004|pages=199\u2013200}}</ref>\n\nJohann Sebastian Bach set the chorale prelude \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" as the third chorale of the ''[[Great Eighteen Chorale Preludes]]'', with two early settings from his period in [[Weimar]] (BWV&nbsp;653a and BWV&nbsp;653b) and a third reworking in [[Leipzig]] from 1740\u20131750, taken from the autograph manuscript of [[BWV 653]].<ref>{{harvnb|Williams|2003|pages=347\u2013351}}</ref>\nThe same melancholic sarabande-like music in the chorale prelude can be heard in Bach's closing movements of the monumental ''Passions'': the increasing [[chromaticism]] and passing dissonances create a mood of pathos.<ref>{{harvnb|Stinson|2001|pages=78\u201380}}</ref>  Bach's project for the ''[[Orgelb\u00fcchlein]],'' dating from his period in [[Weimar]], includes two blank manuscript pages for \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" (pages 116\u2013117, Christian Life and Conduct) that were never set.<ref>{{harvnb|Stinson|1999|pages=2\u20139}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:P802-Walther-Manuscript-BWV653b-first-page--An-Wasserfl\u00fcssen-Babylon.jpg|BWV&nbsp;653b, with a double pedal part (not necessarily by Bach)\nFile:Autograph-Manuscript-Johann-Sebastian-Bach-P271-start-An-Wasserfl\u00fcssen-Babylon-BWV653.jpg|Autograph manuscript of Bach's BWV&nbsp;653\n</gallery>\n\n=== Bach and Reincken ===   \n[[File:ReinckenAnWasser.jpg|thumb|upright|Reincken's organ chorale \"An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon\" in a tablature copy once owned by Bach]]\nStinson's describes a concert in 1720, when Bach extemporised for \"almost half an hour\" on ''An Wasserfl\u00fcssen Babylon'' at the organ loft of [[St. Catherine's Church, Hamburg]], with a well-known comment of Reincken, written 2 years before his death: \"I thought that this art was dead, but I see that in you it still lives.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Bach|1998|p=302}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stinson|2001|pages=78\u201380}}</ref>\n\nBach wrote three versions of the third chorale of the \"Great Eighteen Chorale Preludes\". The coda of the last version, dating from his last decade in [[Leipzig]], shares some compositional features of Reincken's chorale prelude: the ornamental descending flourish at the end of Reincken's coda\n\n::[[File:Coda-Reincken-Chorale-Prelude-An-Wasserfl\u00fcssen-Babylon-Organ.jpg|frameless|upright=2.7]]\n\ncan be compared with Bach's closing coda of BWV&nbsp;653 with scales in [[contrary motion]] in the lower manual and pedal.\n\n::[[File:Autograph-Manuscript-Bach-P271-coda-An-Wasserfl\u00fcssen-Babylon-BWV653.jpg|Coda of BWV&nbsp;653|frameless|upright=2.7]]\n\nAs Stinson writes, \"It is hard not to believe that this correspondence represents an act of homage.\" <ref>{{harvnb|Stinson|2001|pages=78\u201380}}</ref> Despite being composed in Leipzig within the traditions of Thuringia, however, Bach's contemplative \"mesmerising\" mood is far removed from his earlier improvisatory compositions in Hamburg and Reincken's chorale fantasia: the later chorale prelude is understated, with its [[cantus firmus]] subtly embellished.<ref> {{harvnb|Geck|2006|pages=507\u2013509}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Williams|2003|pages=348\u2013349}}</ref>\n\nReincken's extended [[chorale fantasia]] elaborates the hymn tune with a broad variety of techniques.{{sfn|Shannon|2012|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GB64QIHirTEC&pg=PA207 207]}} The young Johann Sebastian Bach owned a copy of this work when he studied with [[Georg B\u00f6hm]] in 1700. Bach's copy, in [[organ tablature]], was rediscovered in 2005 at the [[Herzogin Anna Amalia Bibliothek]] in [[Weimar]] by [[Michael Maul]] and Peter Wollny. These scholars believe the tablature to be in Bach's hand, which is however doubted by Kirsten Bei\u00dfwenger. If it is, it would be one of Bach's oldest extant manuscripts.<ref name=\"Klassik-Stiftung\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Bach|2006}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Stinson|2012}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Williams|2016}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Yearsley|2009}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Bei\u00dfwenger|2017}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Rose|2017|pages=226\u2013227}}</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{ill|Eduard Emil Koch|de}}: ''Geschichte des Kirchenlieds und Kirchengesangs der christlichen, insbesondere der deutschen evangelischen Kirche''. Vol. 8: [https://books.google.com/books?id=U2AOAQAAIAAJ ''Zweiter Haupttheil: Die Lieder und Weisen''.]  Stuttgart: Belser, 1876 (3rd edition), pp.&nbsp;526\u2013528. {{in lang|de}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist | 2\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Axmacher\">{{harvnb|Axmacher|Fischer|2002}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Terry\">{{cite web\n| last = Terry\n| first = Charles Sanford\n| url = https://openlibrary.org/works/OL1299979W/Bach's_chorals\n| title = Bach's Chorals. Part III: The Hymns and Hymn Melodies of the Organ Works.\n| website = [[The Open Library]]\n| accessdate = \n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Klassik-Stiftung\">{{cite web |url=http://www.klassik-stiftung.de/service/presse/termine-und-pressemitteilungen/detailansicht-archiv/?tx_news_pi1%5Bnews%5D=277&tx_news_pi1%5Bcontroller%5D=News&tx_news_pi1%5Baction%5D=detail&cHash=202347685c9769f535e6a34a64bbf92d |title=Earliest Music Manuscripts by Johann Sebastian Bach Discovered |last=Adler |first=Margit |date=31 August 2006 |website=www.klassik-stiftung.de |publisher=Klassik Stiftung Weimar}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"W\u00fcrttemberg\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.lieder-vom-glauben.de/cms/startseite/?key=d7e187e487f34f132a5ccc9649bb8a4e\n| title = Ein L\u00e4mmlein geht und tr\u00e4gt die Schuld\n| publisher = W\u00fcrttembergische Landeskirche\n| language = German\n| accessdate = 24 February 2018\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{citation|title=The History of Keyboard Music to 1700|first=Willi|last=Apel|authorlink=Willi Apel|translator=Hans Tischler|publisher=[[Indiana University Press]]|year=1972|isbn=0253211417|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofkeyboar00will}}\n*{{citation| last = Axmacher| first = Elke| last2 = Fischer| first2 = Michael| editor-last = Hahn| editor-first = Gerhard| editor2-last = Henkys| editor2-first = J\u00fcrgen| chapter-url = https://books.google.de/books?id=jT037Ls6vE4C&pg=PA60| cha